    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, don't panic, my dear! A broken Hollandaise is a classic case of \"the eggs were too shy to talk to the butter,\" and it's a very common occurrence. You're not out of luck; you just need to find the right \"grooming\" to bring the sauce back to life.\n\nFirst, let's address the \"oily\" look. That separation is usually just the fat droplets trying to escape, not a sign of permanent ruin. If you shake it vigorously, you might see them swirl back together, but the best fix is to give it a gentle, slow simmer. This will help the emulsion re-stick, turning that oily mess back into a silky, golden sauce.\n\nNow, for the \"can I fix it?\" part: Yes, absolutely! The secret lies in patience and a little bit of magic. While you simmer the sauce, you can add a splash of warm milk or cream to help stabilize the fats. If the sauce is too thick, a pinch of lemon juice or a tiny bit of white wine can help re-balance the acidity and fat content.\n\nJust remember, once the sauce is back together, you must keep it warm and gently stir to prevent",
